WEBVTT

00:00.994 --> 00:04.118
Friends, welcome to Word on Fire Catholic Ministries.

00:04.699 --> 00:18.377
Word on Fire is an apostolate dedicated to the mission of evangelization, using media both old and new to share the faith on every continent and to facilitate an encounter with Christ and His Church.

00:19.118 --> 00:26.668
The efforts of Word on Fire engage the culture and bring the transformative power of God's Word where it is most needed.

00:26.708 --> 00:27.890
Today,

00:27.970 --> 00:35.983
We invite you to join Bishop Robert Barron as he preaches the gospel and shares the warmth and light of Christ with each one of us.

00:39.469 --> 00:40.110
Peace be with you.

00:40.351 --> 00:54.514
Friends, for this 30th Sunday, ordinary time, we are treated to this wonderful and deeply challenging parable from the 18th chapter of Luke, the famous parable of the Pharisee and the publican, the Pharisee and the

00:54.658 --> 00:55.399
tax collector.

00:55.860 --> 00:58.965
We're meant to see in this deceptively simple story.

00:58.985 --> 01:01.268
It's actually chock full of spiritual insight.

01:01.829 --> 01:08.359
We're meant to see a basic principle in the spiritual order, one that is extremely clarifying.

01:08.940 --> 01:11.143
And let me just state it right at the outset here.

01:11.364 --> 01:11.965
Here's the principle.

01:13.707 --> 01:20.658
The ego is meant to revolve around God, not God around the ego.

01:21.602 --> 01:22.203
Let me say that again.

01:22.844 --> 01:25.888
So the ego, think of like a Copernican revolution here.

01:26.409 --> 01:32.276
The ego is meant to revolve around God, not God around the ego.

01:33.378 --> 01:38.545
And just as you know, they say, if you went out in deep space and all that and you're trying to turn it out, what's going around what?

01:39.046 --> 01:40.828
It might not be immediately clear.

01:41.169 --> 01:43.872
It can be deceptive, you know, what's circling what?

01:44.453 --> 01:51.122
And the same is true in the spiritual order, I think, is sometimes the people that look the most religious

01:52.098 --> 01:53.399
actually aren't very religious.

01:53.760 --> 01:59.926
And the people that look, boy, he's a million miles from God, they're actually the ones who are in the right spiritual space.

02:01.048 --> 02:14.542
And now looking at ourselves to ask that very simple but very penetrating question, and I'll be honest, be honest, is God revolving around me or am I revolving around God?

02:16.024 --> 02:21.650
See, if God's revolving around me, that means that my ego

02:22.626 --> 02:27.793
my life project, my desires, my plans come first.

02:28.294 --> 02:29.596
They're the center of gravity.

02:30.397 --> 02:33.622
Everything else is contributing to that or threatening it in some way.

02:34.403 --> 02:36.506
Now, if I believe in God, you say, OK, great.

02:36.626 --> 02:40.111
God can be very helpful to my plans.

02:40.932 --> 02:42.354
I want to do X, Y, and Z.

02:42.555 --> 02:45.819
And God can really be useful to me in this regard.

02:45.859 --> 02:47.762
And maybe God will help me.

02:48.386 --> 02:54.333
And if things aren't going well, well, I can get pretty mad at him because you're supposed to be helping my ego project.

02:55.374 --> 02:58.838
All right, may I suggest that's the wrong way to go through life.

02:59.598 --> 03:00.259
What's the right way?

03:01.380 --> 03:04.704
And again, it's a Copernican revolution, which can be very wrenching.

03:06.686 --> 03:17.138
Is it has to be the case that I, with my projects and plans and desires and hopes and all that, I, my ego revolves around God.

03:18.562 --> 03:22.546
God is the proper center of gravity for my life.

03:23.307 --> 03:26.290
My life makes sense in terms of God.

03:27.931 --> 03:32.155
The question, therefore, is not, well, are things going according to my plan?

03:33.757 --> 03:40.043
Rather, the question becomes, is my life going according to God's plan?

03:41.404 --> 03:45.909
Now, again, I'm addressing only sinners here, and I'm one of you.

03:46.149 --> 03:47.250
We're all sinners.

03:47.490 --> 03:55.600
which means we are very, very easily drawn out of this right relationship into the wrong relationship.

03:55.620 --> 04:06.833
And I'll suggest to you, when you go to confession or if you talk to a spiritual friend or a spiritual director or in your own prayer, ask this question with brutal honesty.

04:08.315 --> 04:12.200
Am I revolving around God or is God revolving around me?

04:12.240 --> 04:15.684
Everything else will flow from that.

04:15.704 --> 04:15.964
Okay?

04:16.485 --> 04:17.426
That's the principle.

04:17.698 --> 04:24.034
Now, let's look at this parable with the principal mind because it's bringing out various dimensions of it in a very clarifying way.

04:24.857 --> 04:27.524
So we hear Jesus address the parable to whom?

04:28.225 --> 04:32.035
To those who are convinced of their own righteousness and despise everyone else.

04:32.396 --> 04:33.439
We'll see right away.

04:33.459 --> 04:34.642
That gives away the game.

04:35.010 --> 04:40.757
If you say, well, boy, thank God for religion because the one thing it's done is convinced me of my own righteousness.

04:41.157 --> 04:48.045
Well, then your moral project and your ego project is at the center of gravity.

04:48.585 --> 04:51.328
And they despised everybody else.

04:51.349 --> 04:55.533
Well, now my religion is becoming a source of aggression toward others.

04:56.675 --> 05:01.820
All right, two important clues that you are in the wrong relationship vis-a-vis God.

05:01.840 --> 05:03.282
Okay, so then here's the parable.

05:04.002 --> 05:06.145
Two people went up to the temple area to pray.

05:06.165 --> 05:07.548
He said, okay, that's a good thing to pray.

05:07.688 --> 05:08.629
Yes, it is, indeed.

05:09.671 --> 05:12.115
One was a Pharisee, the other was a tax collector.

05:12.135 --> 05:16.241
I mentioned this before, right away we think, oh, Pharisee, bad guy.

05:16.942 --> 05:18.745
No, no, you have to reverse this thing.

05:18.885 --> 05:20.528
In Jesus' time, just the opposite.

05:20.908 --> 05:24.574
If you saw a Pharisee, the presumption would be, well, this is a good person.

05:24.634 --> 05:29.682
This is someone who's taking religion and the law very seriously.

05:30.306 --> 05:31.288
a tax collector.

05:31.668 --> 05:35.314
Again, we're conditioned by so many centuries of reading the New Testament, though.

05:35.374 --> 05:36.816
Tax collectors are really good guys.

05:37.277 --> 05:37.918
No, they're not.

05:37.938 --> 05:38.780
They're bad guys.

05:39.260 --> 05:40.803
And they were indeed bad people.

05:41.304 --> 05:45.430
Jews collaborating with the Romans, skimming off the top for their own benefit.

05:45.831 --> 05:48.195
They were deeply abusive to their own people.

05:48.355 --> 05:54.906
So you've got what everyone took to be a good man going into pray, the Pharisee, and a bad man going into pray.

05:55.286 --> 05:57.169
Okay.

05:57.189 --> 05:57.650
Now listen,

05:58.562 --> 06:03.529
The Pharisee took up his position and spoke this prayer to himself.

06:04.010 --> 06:05.813
Both are really interesting details, I think.

06:06.234 --> 06:07.596
So look, he's a Pharisee.

06:07.996 --> 06:09.458
He's a professional religious person.

06:09.518 --> 06:13.264
So he walks into the temple, this very holy place, God's dwelling place.

06:13.284 --> 06:15.087
But he's not overwhelmed by that.

06:15.107 --> 06:17.671
He feels pretty cocky, pretty confident.

06:17.691 --> 06:19.113
I'll just take up my position.

06:19.253 --> 06:20.215
I belong here.

06:20.275 --> 06:22.278
Well, here's an interesting question.

06:22.378 --> 06:25.202
And I pose it to you and to me.

06:26.146 --> 06:32.413
When's the last time that you walked into a church where the Blessed Sacrament is reserved, where Jesus is really present?

06:33.194 --> 06:36.037
Last time you walked into a church and really felt unworthy.

06:37.979 --> 06:42.064
Maybe you genuflect it and that's kind of, it's a gesture of that, of deference to the Lord.

06:42.885 --> 06:48.692
But when's the last time that you almost felt a sense of like fear and I don't belong here.

06:49.072 --> 06:50.834
I'm in the holy presence of God.

06:51.842 --> 06:55.208
See, the Pharisee gives every indication of being in the wrong space.

06:55.889 --> 06:58.554
I mean, he just walks in with a blind confidence.

07:00.137 --> 07:02.441
I don't know, who's revolving around whom at this point?

07:03.903 --> 07:07.570
Is religion becoming a way for him to aggrandize his own ego?

07:08.051 --> 07:14.322
And then that beautiful detail and so subtly expressed that he spoke this prayer to himself.

07:14.658 --> 07:26.494
So prayer, the raising of the mind and heart to God, see, is meant to get you out of your ego, break free of the black hole of your self-preoccupation, and get you in touch with God.

07:26.975 --> 07:29.519
It's meant to leave the ego behind.

07:29.599 --> 07:35.787
It's meant to put the ego into this relationship of revolution around God.

07:36.328 --> 07:41.115
But see, all his prayer does is aggrandize himself.

07:41.215 --> 07:43.538
So he spoke the prayer to himself.

07:45.122 --> 07:46.103
Ask yourself the question.

07:46.383 --> 07:47.584
I'll ask it of myself too.

07:48.485 --> 07:53.190
When we pray, is the prayer going up to God?

07:53.711 --> 07:57.234
Is it drawing us up like incense to the Lord?

07:57.294 --> 08:00.758
Or is the prayer turning in?

08:00.818 --> 08:08.906
In other words, is it self-serving, self-preoccupied, a grandizing to the ego?

08:09.827 --> 08:13.330
Well, in his case, we hear, because here's how he prays,

08:13.922 --> 08:21.952
Oh God, I thank you that I am not like the rest of humanity, greedy, dishonest, adulterous, or even like this tax collector.

08:22.352 --> 08:23.433
I fast twice a week.

08:23.554 --> 08:25.316
I pay ties on my whole income.

08:26.597 --> 08:30.362
Okay, so it's exaggerated here to make the point, but you get it.

08:30.382 --> 08:35.448
He's someone who is really enjoying being religious.

08:36.549 --> 08:36.689
Why?

08:36.709 --> 08:39.132
Because it's making him truly happy.

08:39.212 --> 08:40.574
It's really putting him in touch with God.

08:40.774 --> 08:43.858
No, no, no, because it's elevating his ego.

08:45.602 --> 08:53.734
Look, I'm not like the rest of humanity, and my knowledge and practice of the law is serving the end of the elevation of my ego.

08:55.156 --> 08:58.121
And the giveaway is that he's comparing himself to everybody.

08:58.882 --> 09:01.165
Now, do you ever know religious people like this?

09:02.006 --> 09:03.148
Yeah, I've known a few.

09:03.469 --> 09:06.393
And maybe once or twice, I've been that religious person.

09:07.575 --> 09:15.186
When my knowledge of the law is used, not to break free of the black hole of egotism.

09:15.746 --> 09:22.335
but is used precisely as a weapon of aggression, a means of comparing myself to others.

09:22.555 --> 09:23.757
See, that's the giveaway.

09:24.838 --> 09:26.140
Okay, so we see him.

09:26.861 --> 09:33.751
He's someone whose ego is the center and God at best is kind of a little satellite revolving around his ego.

09:34.472 --> 09:42.182
No, secondly, but the task collector stood off at a distance, would not even raise his eyes to heaven.

09:42.743 --> 09:44.946
Go back again to the question I just asked about

09:45.666 --> 09:53.559
coming into church, Catholic church, where the Lord is really truly and substantially present.

09:53.579 --> 09:58.447
When is the last time you felt unworthy to be in His presence?

09:58.467 --> 10:02.815
If it's been a long time, that's a problem.

10:02.835 --> 10:07.282
When have you felt truly and in a beautiful sense, ashamed

10:08.002 --> 10:08.723
before God.

10:08.803 --> 10:13.408
And again, I'm not trying to urge you to play a game of, oh, God is a horrible tyrant.

10:13.809 --> 10:18.754
I mean, that salutary feeling that you're not where you're supposed to be.

10:18.814 --> 10:23.480
And in the presence of the all holy God, you're unworthy.

10:25.542 --> 10:26.263
When's the last time?

10:27.164 --> 10:28.946
Here's a little detail I find really interesting.

10:29.266 --> 10:36.114
You know in the liturgy at the beginning, when we're seeking God's mercy, and we say, Lord have mercy, Christ have mercy, Lord have mercy.

10:36.834 --> 10:39.477
It's been referred to as a liturgical stammer.

10:40.658 --> 10:44.002
How somebody might act in the presence of a great king.

10:44.783 --> 10:47.946
Imagine a very ordinary person coming in, something in the presence of the great king.

10:48.386 --> 10:52.791
He's not gonna stand there like the Pharisee and give this, you know, really cocky, confident speech.

10:53.512 --> 10:58.758
No, no, he's gonna bow down and probably stammer out what he wants.

10:59.599 --> 11:02.802
And so we do that, Lord have mercy, Christ have mercy, Lord have mercy.

11:04.354 --> 11:07.659
Just wrote words or reflective of a real attitude.

11:09.722 --> 11:14.148
He beat his breast and prayed, oh God, be merciful to me, a sinner.

11:14.209 --> 11:18.375
I've talked to you before about the Jesus prayer, which I love.

11:19.396 --> 11:22.020
In fact, I have a little Jesus prayer rope.

11:22.180 --> 11:26.667
They use them in the Eastern Christian traditions, where you just you count the Jesus prayer.

11:27.208 --> 11:28.770
And it's mimicking this man.

11:29.471 --> 11:34.098
You say, Lord Jesus Christ, Son of the living God, have mercy on me, a sinner.

11:34.274 --> 11:35.035
That's the whole prayer.

11:36.116 --> 11:40.740
And you pray it once, you pray it twice, you pray it 10 times, you pray it 50 times.

11:40.760 --> 11:41.842
The rope I have is 100.

11:42.062 --> 11:51.171
And I woke up in the middle of the night last night, and that's a way I have a kind of lulling myself to sleep, but I'll pray that Jesus' prayer.

11:51.691 --> 11:54.834
Lord Jesus Christ, the living God, have mercy on me as sinner.

11:57.097 --> 12:02.482
That's a great corrective to the Pharisaical tendency.

12:03.106 --> 12:10.097
When you can begin your relationship with God like this man, look, he's a bad man and he is.

12:10.137 --> 12:12.020
We're all bad people.

12:12.040 --> 12:15.085
We've all sinned and fallen short of the glory of God.

12:15.125 --> 12:16.126
We're all bad people.

12:17.228 --> 12:18.170
So how do we start?

12:18.350 --> 12:24.199
If you wanna get the spiritual life now in right order, you wanna reverse this Copernican relationship.

12:24.540 --> 12:28.185
You want your own ego revolving your own God's purposes.

12:28.446 --> 12:31.250
A really good place to start is right there.

12:32.194 --> 12:33.596
Start praying it today, tonight.

12:34.697 --> 12:39.723
Lord Jesus Christ, Son of the living God, have mercy on me, a sinner.

12:40.784 --> 12:48.272
Saint Bertha talks about the kiss of the feet, followed by the kiss of the hand, and only finally the kiss of the mouth.

12:48.352 --> 12:54.499
What he means is, spiritual life begins with this abject request for mercy.

12:54.539 --> 12:55.921
That's the kiss of the Lord's feet.

12:56.582 --> 13:00.306
It continues with the kiss of the hand, which means walking the,

13:00.770 --> 13:09.602
the difficult and challenging path of discipleship and only after that long period are you perhaps ready for that kiss of intimacy with the Lord.

13:10.804 --> 13:20.136
Okay, if you find yourself like the Pharisee and we all are to some degree, you find yourself in this wrong Copernican relationship and you want to turn it around.

13:20.797 --> 13:23.080
That's a really good place to start.

13:23.761 --> 13:30.450
Go into church, maybe as you genuflect, be very aware of your unworthiness before the Lord.

13:31.714 --> 13:38.721
and then begin praying, Lord Jesus Christ, Son of a living God, have mercy on me a sinner.

13:39.702 --> 13:44.326
You'll find the center of gravity in your spiritual life begin to change.

13:45.528 --> 13:46.128
And God bless you.

13:50.993 --> 13:54.597
Thank you for listening to this week's homily from Bishop Robert Barron.

13:54.977 --> 14:00.082
For more resources from Bishop Barron, please visit wordonfire.org.

